  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the Prime Minister of India is a constitutional post. The role of the Prime Minister is defined in the Constitution of India, specifically in Articles 75 and 84. The Prime Minister is the head of the government and is responsible for running the executive branch, coordinating the functions of the government, and representing the country in various matters. The Prime Minister is appointed by the President of India and must be a member of the Lok Sabha (the lower house of Parliament) or, in certain situations, the Rajya Sabha (the upper house). Thus, the position is established and governed by constitutional provisions.",
